SIMPLE: settle
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Settle
<hw>Set"tle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>setel</ets>,
<ets>setil</ets>, a seat, AS. <ets>setl</ets>: akin to OHG.
<ets>sezzal</ets>, G. <ets>sessel</ets>, Goth. <ets>sitls</ets>, and E.
<ets>sit</ets>. ⟦root⟧154. See <er>Sit</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
seat of any kind.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Upon the
<xex>settle</xex> of his majesty⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Hampole.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A bench; especially, a bench with a high
back.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A place made lower than the rest; a wide step or
platform lower than some other part.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And from the bottom upon the ground, even to the lower
<qex>settle</qex>, shall be two cubits, and the breadth one cubit.</q>
<rj><qau>Ezek. xliii. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Settle bed</b></col>, <cd>a bed convertible into a
seat.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Settle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Settle
<hw>Set"tle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Settled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Settling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>setlen</ets>, AS. <ets>setlan</ets>. ⟦root⟧154. See
<er>Settle</er>, <pos>n.</pos> In senses 7, 8, and 9 perhaps confused
with OE. <ets>sahtlen</ets> to reconcile, AS. <ets>sahtlian</ets>, fr.
<ets>saht</ets> reconciliation, <ets>sacon</ets> to contend, dispute.
Cf. <er>Sake</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To place in a fixed or
permanent condition; to make firm, steady, or stable; to establish; to
fix; esp., to establish in life; to fix in business, in a home, or the
like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And he <qex>settled</qex> his countenance steadfastly upon him,
until he was ashamed.</q> <rj><qau>2 Kings viii. 11. (Rev. Ver.)
</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The father thought the time drew on⟦br⟧
Of <qex>setting</qex> in the world his only son.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To establish in the pastoral office; to ordain or
install as pastor or rector of a church, society, or parish; <as>as, to
<ex>settle</ex> a minister</as>.</def> <mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to be no longer in a disturbed condition;
to render quiet; to still; to calm; to compose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God <qex>settled</qex> then the huge whale-bearing lake.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hoping that sleep might <qex>settle</qex> his brains.</q>
<rj><qau>Bunyan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To clear of dregs and impurities by causing them to
sink; to render pure or clear; -- said of a liquid; <as>as, to
<ex>settle</ex> coffee, or the grounds of coffee</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To restore or bring to a smooth, dry, or passable
condition; -- said of the ground, of roads, and the like; <as>as, clear
weather <ex>settles</ex> the roads</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To cause to sink; to lower; to depress; hence, also,
to render close or compact; <as>as, to <ex>settle</ex> the contents of a
barrel or bag by shaking it</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To determine, as something which is exposed to doubt
or question; to free from unscertainty or wavering; to make sure, firm,
or constant; to establish; to compose; to quiet; <as>as, to
<ex>settle</ex> the mind when agitated; to <ex>settle</ex> questions of
law; to <ex>settle</ex> the succession to a throne; to <ex>settle</ex>
an allowance</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It will <qex>settle</qex> the wavering, and confirm the
doubtful.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To adjust, as something in discussion; to make up;
to compose; to pacify; <as>as, to <ex>settle</ex> a
quarrel</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To adjust, as accounts; to liquidate; to balance;
<as>as, to <ex>settle</ex> an account</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>Hence, to pay; <as>as, to <ex>settle</ex> a
bill</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>Abbott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>To plant with inhabitants; to colonize; to people;
<as>as, the French first <ex>settled</ex> Canada; the Puritans
<ex>settled</ex> New England; Plymouth was <ex>settled</ex> in
1620.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To settle on</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To
settle upon</b></col></mcol>, <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>to confer upon by
permanent grant; to assure to.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧I . . . have <xex>settled
upon</xex> him a good annuity.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Addison.</au> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>to choose; to decide on; -- sometimes with the implication that the
choice is not ideal, but the best available.</cd> -- <col><b>To settle
the land</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to cause it to sink, or
appear lower, by receding from it.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To fix; establish; regulate; arrange; compose;
adjust; determine; decide.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Settle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Settle
<hw>Set"tle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become fixed or
permanent; to become stationary; to establish one's self or itself; to
assume a lasting form, condition, direction, or the like, in place of a
temporary or changing state.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wind came about and <qex>settled</qex> in the west.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Chyle . . . runs through all the intermediate colors until it
<qex>settles</qex> in an intense red.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fix one's residence; to establish a dwelling
place or home; <as>as, the Saxons who <ex>settled</ex> in
Britain</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To enter into the married state, or the state of a
householder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As people marry now and <qex>settle</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be established in an employment or profession;
<as>as, to <ex>settle</ex> in the practice of law</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To become firm, dry, and hard, as the ground after
the effects of rain or frost have disappeared; <as>as, the roads
<ex>settled</ex> late in the spring</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To become clear after being turbid or obscure; to
clarify by depositing matter held in suspension; <as>as, the weather
<ex>settled</ex>; wine <ex>settles</ex> by standing</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A government, on such occasions, is always thick before it
<qex>settles</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To sink to the bottom; to fall to the bottom, as
dregs of a liquid, or the sediment of a reserveir.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To sink gradually to a lower level; to subside, as
the foundation of a house, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To become calm; to cease from agitation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till the fury of his highness <qex>settle</qex>,⟦br⟧
Come not before him.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To adjust differences or accounts; to come to an
agreement; <as>as, he has <ex>settled</ex> with his
creditors</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>To make a jointure for a wife.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He sighs with most success that <qex>settles</qex> well.</q>
<rj><qau>Garth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Settledness</ent>⟦br⟧
